    <hr>
    <h2><strong>1. AMTS &mdash; Abbreviated Mental Test Score</strong></h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Quick screen for cognitive impairment
          (often in elderly or acute settings).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Questions:</strong> 10 items &mdash; e.g., age, date of
          birth, current year, time, address recall, recognition of people,
          historical dates, etc.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Scoring:</strong> 1 point per correct answer &rarr; <strong>&lt;8/10
            suggests cognitive impairment</strong> (needs further assessment).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Strengths:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Very quick (2&ndash;3 min)</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Widely used in A&amp;E, acute medicine</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Doesn&rsquo;t differentiate acute delirium from chronic dementia.</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Cultural bias possible in some questions.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr>
    <h2><strong>2. 4AT &mdash; 4 A&rsquo;s Test</strong></h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Rapid delirium screen (designed for acute
          hospitals, especially elderly patients).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Domains:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p><strong>Alertness</strong> (normal, abnormal, drowsy)</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p><strong>AMT4</strong> &mdash; 4-item orientation (age, date of
              birth, place, year)</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p><strong>Attention</strong> &mdash; e.g., months of the year
              backwards</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p><strong>Acute change or fluctuating course</strong></p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Scoring:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>0 = unlikely delirium/cognitive impairment</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>1&ndash;3 = possible cognitive impairment</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>&ge;4 = possible delirium (needs clinical confirmation)</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Strengths:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Takes <strong>&lt;2 minutes</strong></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Picks up both delirium and dementia risk</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>No need for patient cooperation if unresponsive (alertness scored
              visually)</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Still a screen &mdash; not diagnostic</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Needs good collateral history for &ldquo;acute change&rdquo;</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr>
    <h2><strong>3. CAM &mdash; Confusion Assessment Method</strong></h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Gold-standard <em>bedside diagnostic</em>
          algorithm for <strong>delirium</strong>.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Criteria:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>Acute onset &amp; fluctuating course <strong>AND</strong></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Inattention <strong>AND</strong></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Either disorganised thinking <strong>OR</strong> altered level
              of consciousness</p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Scoring:</strong> Positive CAM = delirium likely; needs
          urgent management.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Strengths:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Well validated, diagnostic rather than screening</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Can be used repeatedly to track changes</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Limitations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>Takes longer (5&ndash;10 min) than 4AT</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>Requires some training to use correctly</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr>
    <h3><strong>Summary Table</strong></h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Tool</th>
          <th>Time</th>
          <th>Focus</th>
          <th>Best For</th>
          <th>Cut-off</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>AMTS</td>
          <td>2&ndash;3m</td>
          <td>Cognitive impairment (any cause)</td>
          <td>Quick screen in ED/ward</td>
          <td>&lt;8/10</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>4AT</td>
          <td>&lt;2m</td>
          <td>Delirium &amp; dementia risk</td>
          <td>Acute hospital settings</td>
          <td>&ge;4 delirium likely</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>CAM</td>
          <td>5&ndash;10m</td>
          <td>Diagnostic delirium</td>
          <td>Confirming delirium after screen</td>
          <td>N/A</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <hr>
